<p align="right"><b>August 11, 1998</b>
<p><center><h2>Anti-U.S. Group spells out Demands</h2></center>
<p>
<P>The “Liberation Army of the Islamic sanctuaries” (<I>Jaysh Tahrir al-Muqaddasat
al-Islamiyyah</I>), the enigmatic Islamic group that claimed responsibility
for the bombing of the U.S. embassies has issued a list of demands.&nbsp;
In statements sent to Radio France International and to the Cairo bureau
of <I>Agence France Press</I>, the group called for U.S. forces to leave
Saudi Arabia, and for the release of Islamic militants. The group's demands,
as published by the <I>Agence France Press </I>included the following:
the withdrawal of Americans--military and civilian--from Saudi Arabia;
the release of Islamists detained in the United States, Israel and Saudi
Arabia--in particular the jailed Sheikh Omar Abdel-Rahman; the cessation
of American support of Israel; and an end to economic sanctions imposed
on "certain Moslem countries."

<P>The group announced that it would "pursue U.S. forces and strike at
U.S. interests everywhere until its demands were satisfied."&nbsp; The
group claimed to owe its inspiration from "fatwas and contemporary moslem
theologians, including Sheikh Omar Abdel-Rahman . . .and statements by
Sheikh Osama bin Ladin."

<P><B>Source: Agence France Press</B>
